      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Testability actions",
      "pos": [
        469,
        488
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In order to simulate an unreliable infrastructure, Service Fabric provides developers with ways to simulate various real world failures and state transitions.",
      "pos": [
        489,
        647
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These are exposed as Testability actions.",
      "pos": [
        648,
        689
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The actions are the low level APIs that cause a specific fault injection, state transition or validation.",
      "pos": [
        690,
        795
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Combining these actions, a service developer can write comprehensive test scenarios for your services.",
      "pos": [
        796,
        898
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service Fabric provides some common test scenarios out of the box composed of these actions.",
      "pos": [
        900,
        992
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is highly recommended to utilize these built-in scenarios, which are carefully chosen to test common state transitions and failure cases.",
      "pos": [
        993,
        1133
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, actions can be used to create custom test scenarios when you want to add coverage for scenarios that are either not covered by the built-in scenarios yet or custom tailored for your application.",
      "pos": [
        1134,
        1337
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "C# implementation of the actions are found in the System.Fabric.Testability.dll assembly.",
      "pos": [
        1339,
        1428
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Testability PowerShell module is found in the Microsoft.ServiceFabric.Testability.Powershell.dll assembly.",
      "pos": [
        1429,
        1539
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As part of runtime installation the ServiceFabricTestability PowerShell module is installed to allow for easy use.",
      "pos": [
        1540,
        1654
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Graceful vs. ungraceful fault actions",
      "pos": [
        1659,
        1696
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Testability actions are classified into two major buckets:",
      "pos": [
        1697,
        1755
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Ungraceful faults: These faults simulate failures like machine restarts and process crashes.",
      "pos": [
        1759,
        1851
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In such cases of failures, the execution context of process stops abruptly.",
      "pos": [
        1852,
        1927
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means no cleanup of state can run before the application starts up again.",
      "pos": [
        1928,
        2006
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Graceful faults: These faults simulate graceful actions like replica moves and drops triggered by load balancing.",
      "pos": [
        2010,
        2123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In such cases the service gets notification of close and can cleanup state before exiting.",
      "pos": [
        2124,
        2214
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For better quality validation, run the service and business workload while inducing various graceful and ungraceful faults.",
      "pos": [
        2216,
        2339
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Ungraceful faults exercise scenarios where the service process abruptly exits in the middle of some workflow.",
      "pos": [
        2340,
        2449
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This tests  the recovery path once the service replica is restored by Service Fabric.",
      "pos": [
        2450,
        2535
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This will help test data consistency and whether the service state is maintained correctly after failures.",
      "pos": [
        2536,
        2642
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The other set of failures i.e. the graceful failures test that the service correctly reacts to replicas being moved around by Service Fabric.",
      "pos": [
        2643,
        2784
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This tests handling of cancellation in the RunAsync method.",
      "pos": [
        2785,
        2844
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The service needs to check for the Cancellation token being set, correctly save its state and exit the RunAsync method.",
      "pos": [
        2845,
        2964
      ]
    },
